<misra_rule>
The target MISRA C 2023 Rule 17.8 is: A function parameter should not be modified.
Note that the object referred to by a pointer parameter may be modified, but the pointer itself shall not be modified.
</misra_rule>
<instruction>
Other agents will judge whether the code follows the MISRA C 2023 guidelines.
They will investigate the code fragments you give.
Your job is to find code fragments in the code that should be investigated to check whether the code follows the MISRA C rule.
</instruction>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- suspicious_frags: The list of suspicious code fragments in the code.
It should contain only the code fragments exists in the code. If you do not find any suspicious code fragments, return an empty list for suspicious_frags
- explanation: The explanation of why other code fragments should NOT be investigated.
It is very important to not miss any suspicious code fragments, so please give a sufficient explanation why other code fragments should not be investigated.
DO NOT give any explanation for the selected suspicious code fragments.
</response format>
<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_SymbolTableDump_Impl:
```c
int32 OS_SymbolTableDump_Impl(const char *filename, size_t SizeLimit)
{
    /*
     * Limiting strictly to POSIX-defined API means there is no defined
     * method to get iterate over the symbol table.
     *
     * Some C libraries do offer an extension to provide this function, so
     * if this becomes a requirement on those platforms, this function
     * might need to move.
     *
     * Currently this is not a widely used/needed feature so it will report
     * unimplemented here.
     */

    return OS_ERR_NOT_IMPLEMENTED;
}
```
</target_code>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are related to the target function OS_SymbolTableDump_Impl:
#define OS_ERR_NOT_IMPLEMENTED (-28)
</additional code>
Please find suspicious code fragments in the code and report them. Other agents can not investigate other fragments that you do not report, so it is very important to find all suspicious fragments without missing any. Report the suspicious fragments AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.
explanation: No suspicious fragments found. The function parameters are: (const char *filename, size_t SizeLimit). The filename parameter is const-qualified, so neither the pointer itself nor the pointed-to object is modified in the body. The function body contains only a comment and a single return of the constant OS_ERR_NOT_IMPLEMENTED (defined as (-28)); there are no assignments, increments, reassignments, pointer arithmetic, or calls that could modify either parameter. Therefore there are no occurrences in this function that could violate MISRA C 2023 Rule 17.8 (a function parameter should not be modified).
